School and Library Subscribers JOIN LOGIN Activate Your Free Trial! stories quizzes galleries lists Literary criticism Written by: Frederick C. Crews Last Updated 12-17-2014 Read View All Media (4) Table of Contents Introduction Functions Historical development Antiquity Medieval period The Renaissance Neoclassicism and its decline Romanticism The late 19th century The 20th century The influence of science Criticism and knowledge Literary criticism, the reasoned consideration of literary works and issues. It applies, as a term, to any argumentation about literature, whether or not specific works are analyzed. Plato’s cautions against the risky consequences of poetic inspiration in general in his Republic are thus often taken as the earliest important example of literary criticism. More strictly construed, the term covers only what has been called “practical criticism,” the interpretation of meaning and the judgment of quality. Criticism in this narrow sense can be distinguished not only from aesthetics (the philosophy of artistic value) but also from other matters that may concern ... (100 of 5,728 words) Images About Us About Our Ads Partner Program Contact Us Privacy Policy Terms of Use ©2016 Encyclopædia Britannica, Inc. To From Subject Comments (Please limit to 900 characters) Cancel MEDIA FOR: literary criticism Citation MLA APA Harvard Chicago Email To: From: Comment: You have successfully emailed this. Error when sending the email. Try again later. To From Subject Comments (Please limit to 900 characters) Cancel Or click Continue to submit anonymously: Continue
